<header class="header">
  <h1>What Is Considered a Short Growing Season?</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Season length is defined by frost — but limited heat makes it short.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, your growing season is bounded by frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
    A “short” growing season means that frost returns sooner — and often that total heat accumulation before frost is limited.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short Growing Season: The Frost Definition</h2>

  <p>
    GrowByDate frames frost dates using 1991–2020 climate normals at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means your listed frost boundaries represent a typical-year planning anchor — not a guarantee.
  </p>

  <p>
    A short growing season often includes:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Less than 120 frost-free days</li>
    <li>Earlier first fall frost</li>
    <li>Later last spring frost</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    You can determine your frost-free window using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    But frost-free days alone do not fully define a short season.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Heat Accumulation Also Matters</h2>

  <p>
    Two regions may both have 110 frost-free days.
  </p>

  <p>
    One may accumulate 2,200 Growing Degree Days (GDD).
    Another may accumulate 1,600.
  </p>

  <p>
    The second region is effectively “shorter” from a crop development standpoint —
    even if the calendar window is identical.
  </p>

  <p>
    As explained in
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>,
    frost defines the boundary, but GDD determines how much development can occur inside it.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical Short-Season Indicators</h2>

  <p>
    While definitions vary by crop and region, short-season climates often have:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>90–120 frost-free days</li>
    <li>Under ~2,000 GDD (base 50) before first frost</li>
    <li>Cool early and late season nighttime temperatures</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    You can estimate your typical seasonal heat accumulation using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    Exact GDD thresholds vary by crop and local climate patterns.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Short Seasons Require Precision</h2>

  <p>
    In long growing seasons, crop maturity margins are often wide.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short growing seasons, margins narrow quickly.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your seasonal heat budget barely exceeds a crop’s requirement,
    small variations in temperature or frost timing can affect maturity.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why short-season planning relies on:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Lower heat-demand varieties</li>
    <li>Careful transplant timing</li>
    <li>Understanding accumulated GDD — not just calendar days</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    For example, see
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>
    for how temperature affects development speed.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short Season vs Cold Climate</h2>

  <p>
    A short growing season does not necessarily mean extreme cold.
  </p>

  <p>
    High elevations, northern latitudes, and interior continental regions can all produce shortened frost windows and reduced heat accumulation.
  </p>

  <p>
    What defines the constraint is not how cold winter gets —
    but how quickly frost returns in fall and how much heat accumulates before it does.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>A short growing season typically means fewer than 120 frost-free days.</li>
    <li>Frost dates are framed at 32°F and 50% probability.</li>
    <li>Growing Degree Days measure how much heat accumulates inside that frost window.</li>
    <li>Limited GDD often defines short-season crop feasibility more than calendar length alone.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short climates, successful crop planning depends on evaluating frost timing and heat accumulation together —
    not treating them as separate factors.
  </p>
</section>